{{More citations needed|date=November 2015}} {{Universiade infobox | Name = XIII Summer Universiade | Logo = | Size = 150 | Optional caption = | Nations participating = 106 | Athletes participating = 2,783 | Events = 11 sports | Opening ceremony = August 24 | Closing ceremony = September 4 | Officially opened by = [[Akihito|Crown Prince Akihito]] | Athlete's Oath = | Judge's Oath = | Torch Lighter = | Stadium = [[Kobe Universiade Memorial Stadium]] }} [[File:151017 Kobe Universiade Memorial Stadium Kobe Japan02n.jpg|thumb|260px|[[Kobe Universiade Memorial Stadium]]]] The '''1985 Summer Universiade''', also known as the XIII Summer [[Universiade]], took place in [[Kobe]], [[Japan]].
==Mascot==
The mascot of the Kobe Universiade, "Unitan", designed by Osamu Tezuka, is a red-crested white [[Crane (bird)|crane]], symbolic of Japan and a good omen. The name was chosen from some 8,000 suggestions received from throughout the country. The name is derived from a combination of 'uni' from 'Universiade' and 'tan' from the Japanese name for red-crested crane, namely 'tancho-tsuru'.
==Gender test== The [[Chromatin|sex chromatin]] test was used at these games to decide on participants' gender; Spanish hurdler [[Maria José Martínez-Patiño]] was declared a man and thus ruled ineligible for the women's events.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ruth Padawer |title=The Humiliating Practice of Sex-Testing Female Athletes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/03/magazine/the-humiliating-practice-of-sex-testing-female-athletes.html?_r=0 |quote= |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 28, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=Ljungqvist>{{cite book|last=Ljungqvist|first=A.|editor=Barbara L. Drinkwater|title=The Encyclopaedia of Sports Medicine: An IOC Medical Commission Publication, Women in Sport|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rPXr-0PUk5gC&pg=PA186|accessdate=2 March 2015|date=2008-04-15|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470756850|pages=183–93|chapter=Gender Verification}}</ref><ref name="Schultz">{{cite book|last=Schultz|first=Jaime|title=Qualifying Times: Points of Change in U.S. Women's Sport|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e-7kAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA112|year=2014|publisher=U of Illinois P|isbn=9780252095962|pages=111–12}}</ref> In agreement with officials who suggested she fake an injury so she could withdraw without publicity, she complied. She later fought, successfully, to have that diagnosis reversed.<ref name=Cole>{{cite book|last=Cole|first=Cheryl L.|editor=Kay Schaffer|others=Sidonie Smith|title=The Olympics at the Millennium: Power, Politics, and the Games|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nMzYdZpk8qMC&pg=PA138|accessdate=2 March 2015|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers UP|isbn=9780813528205|pages=128–46|chapter=One Chromosome Too Many?}}</ref>
